bib_record.title: Study of associated gamma ray from niobium under 14.9 MeV neutron bombardments

free_txt: in Chinese
400 KV pulsed Cockcroft-Walton
accelerator at Beijing Normal University.
Correction applied for
. neutron flux attenuation in sample
. multi-scattering of elastic scattering neutrons
. multi-scattering of inelastic scattering neutrons
. gamma ray absorption in sample
. neutron flux attenuation in target material and
cooling water layer
. correction for solid angle due to surface source as
point source approximation.
A 110.7 cm3 Co-axial Ge-Li detector with
resolution 1.85 keV for 1332.5 keV gamma-ray of Co-60
was used for gamma yields absolute measurement.
In the 100 keV-3 MeV gamma energy range, gamma detector
was absolute calibrated using a set of standard gamma
sources with accuracy 2-3%.
Main error sources as follows:
. <4.0% for neutron flux
absolute efficiency of Ge(Li)
detector in 100 keV-2.6 MeV range.
full energy gamma peak count (dep-
ends on the statistical error of every gamma peak
count)
all corrections described under the
keyword <correction>.
400 KV pulsed Cockcroft-Walton
accelerator at Beijing Normal University.
300 keV deuteron on T-Ti target, average neutron
intensity was 5.0 x 10**8 neutrons/sec.
A Au-Si surface barrier detector was used for
He-4 detection to determine the neutron flux.
Cylindrical metal niobium sample, purity=99.9%,
diameter=3.02 cm, length=3.044 cm, weight=188 grams.
Data taken from Table 2 of Chinese j. of High
Energy Physics and Nuclear Physics(Physica Energiae
Fortis et Physica Nuclearis), vol.13, No.2, 173(1989).
